{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17536238","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17536238"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:05:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:05:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15720"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15720","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15720"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.56,0.09,0.05,0.29]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8411"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62363"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8411","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8411"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15720"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47810"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"675"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"1813"},{"type":"tags","id":"2545"},{"type":"tags","id":"2546"},{"type":"tags","id":"3327"},{"type":"tags","id":"3331"},{"type":"tags","id":"4097"},{"type":"tags","id":"4640"},{"type":"tags","id":"4705"},{"type":"tags","id":"4821"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20258"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34431"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44428"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62363","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62363"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old Aboriginal man from a remote community in the Northern Territory presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of a non-itchy rash. He also reports fatigue, mild fever, and generalised aches. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He works as a bus driver. He reports unprotected sexual intercourse with more than one partner in the past six months.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. There is a copper-coloured maculopapular rash on his trunk and extremities, including his palms and soles. An image of this rash is shown below. There are several painless, enlarged lymph nodes in his neck and groin. Condylomata lata is noted around the anus. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cytomegalovirus (CMV) PCR","T.pallidum enzyme immunoassay (TP EIA)","Human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) serology","Neisseria gonorrhoea nucleic acid amplification test (NAAT)","Rapid plasma reagin (RPR)"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of secondary syphilis, including a copper-coloured maculopapular rash involving palms and soles, generalised lymphadenopathy, condylomata lata, and constitutional symptoms. Secondary syphilis is the systemic stage of syphilis infection (caused by \u003Cem\u003ETreponema pallidum\u003C/em\u003E) occurring at the same time as or up to six months after resolution of the primary chancre. Patients with secondary syphilis are highly infectious.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET.pallidum enzyme immunoassay (TP EIA)\u003C/strong\u003E is the recommended initial screening test for syphilis. It detects specific antibodies against \u003Cem\u003ETreponema pallidum\u003C/em\u003E and has high sensitivity and specificity. Other specific Treponemal tests include Fluorescent Treponemal Antibody Absorption (FTA-ABS) and Treponema pallidum haemagglutination (TPHA). A positive result should be followed by RPR testing to determine disease activity and monitor treatment response.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERapid plasma reagin (RPR)\u003C/strong\u003E is a non-treponemal test. While useful for monitoring disease activity and treatment response, it should not be used as the initial screening test as it can give false positive results in various conditions including pregnancy and autoimmune diseases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHuman immunodeficiency virus (HIV) serology\u003C/strong\u003E should be performed in all patients diagnosed with syphilis due to the high rate of co-infection, but it is not the most appropriate initial test for diagnosing the presenting condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeisseria gonorrhoea nucleic acid amplification test (NAAT)\u003C/strong\u003E is important in the context of sexually transmitted infection screening but would not explain the characteristic features of secondary syphilis present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECytomegalovirus (CMV) PCR\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate as the clinical features are not consistent with CMV infection, which typically causes different symptoms and does not produce the characteristic rash pattern seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERemote Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander communities in Northern Australia have much higher notification rates of sexually transmitted infections. Syphilis is a nationally notifiable condition. It is imperative these cases are reported to the centre for disease control/local public health unit.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Secondary syphilis can present with a copper-coloured maculopapular rash involving palms and soles, lymphadenopathy, and condylomata lata.","T.pallidum enzyme immunoassay (TP EIA) is the preferred initial screening test for syphilis.","Rapid plasma reagin (RPR) is used to monitor treatment response and disease activity."],"references":["Remote Primary Health Care Manuals. Tropical Health Orientation Manual. Alice Springs, NT: Centre for Remote Health; 2020"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47810"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15720"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21181"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21181","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21181"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/c2fr5pdsSVQcFlNppYh5gbdmt26LzW.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/c2fr5pdsSVQcFlNppYh5gbdmt26LzW.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":503,"height":435}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47810","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47810"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-17T18:05:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-17T18:06:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8411"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62363"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"37","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/37"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf46","name":"Sexual Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updated